I will study social work to help children who have been hurt or not taken care of, and to support troubled families. Good values I can give to social work are: service, respect, being ethical, helping others' relationships, and always improving my skills. These values are important for social work and for me.

In high school and college, I saw people hide from their problems and use bad ways to cope. Because of these problems, I chose to study Psychology. After college, I thought about different jobs, but I was not sure what I wanted to do. One day, I met a boy at my friend's house. He was 16 and scared because his parents hurt him. The next day, I went to his parents' house to help. The police could not help, so I talked to the parents. They acted guilty. After this, I thought about working as a social worker to help children like him.

Social justice is also important for social work. Society says each person is important, but we often want to be like others. I do not like this. At school, I protested against unfairness by coloring my hair, wearing special clothes, and standing up against racism and discrimination. I will always fight for social justice.

This paper talks about two ways to look at insomnia. The first way is the biological model. This model talks about the genes and medical parts of sleep problems. The second way is the sociocultural model. This model talks about the environment and how it relates to race, ethnicity, and social status. The paper looks at these models and explains certain research to make them better. It also talks about the good and bad parts of each research.

Sleep problem can be a problem you have with sleeping alone, or it can be related to a mental problem or another health issue. There are types of sleep problems like Dyssomnias and Parasomnias. Dyssomnias are problems with starting or staying asleep. Parasomnias are problems that happen during sleep, like nightmares or sleepwalking. The paper mainly talks about insomnia and some other types of sleep problems related to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep problems talks about genes and the body's way of sleeping. This study looked at mice and found something called the GABAB receptor. This receptor helps with sleep and wakefulness. If it's not working right, it can cause sleep problems. This study shows that the model in mice can be the same as in humans. It also shows that sleep problems might be caused by genes or the environment. If the receptor doesn't work right, it can cause sleep problems and make it hard to do daily tasks.

The sociocultural model looks at how the environment and social status might cause sleep problems. The study talks about how the GABAB receptor can be inherited. If it's not working right, it can cause sleep problems. This can affect school, work, and daily tasks.

This paper talks about three things about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition of the disorder. Next, it explains diagnosis, with common signs or "red flags." Finally, it talks about how teachers can help students with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is when the brain has trouble processing sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain does not understand sounds as it should. This can make it hard to understand speech, especially in noisy places.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s. Researchers in Italy started testing children with communication problems in 1954. In 1961, a scientist named Kimura introduced a test to understand how the brain processes sounds. A conference in 1977 helped researchers study CAPD more.

CAPD can cause problems like not being able to tell where sounds come from, having trouble with similar sounds, not understanding sound patterns, and not noticing changes in speech. It can also make it hard to understand the order of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, a person must take tests and answer questions. There is no one test that always works well. Tests can be simple or more advanced. Some tests ask the person to recognize sounds in a noisy place. Others record sounds in the ear and measure how the person responds.

In the play Twelfth Night, disguise can be helpful for hiding for a long time. But finally, a person must stop the deception, or they will lose themselves. Ending deception can make people feel alone. They may be hurt or angry. Viola in Twelfth Night must disguise herself as a man to protect herself. She is in a new country. She needs to pretend to be a boy to stay safe. But this makes her feel alone. Olivia thinks Cesario (Viola) is a boy. She falls in love with Cesario. Orsino also has feelings for Cesario. This shows that deception can help people find hidden feelings. But is Olivia really in love with Cesario, or just likes how Cesario looks? She quickly changes her love from Cesario to Sebastian, and thinks Cesario is family. This shows Olivia does not love Cesario for who Cesario really is.

German colonial rule was known for its cruelty, especially in the case of the Ovaherero and Nama in South West Africa. The German colonial empire was different in many ways. Educational systems in different colonies were also different. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found many educated Africans. In Kamerun and other colonies, German education was praised. In South West Africa, education was mostly done by missionaries with limited government help. The government in South West Africa mainly supported European education. This had long-term effects on South West Africa. Most of the local population remained uneducated. Many things affected this situation. This paper will discuss these factors and look at new research about settlers' and colonial authorities' attitudes towards native Africans.
Many books have been written about education in the German colonial empire. Most are in German and from the early twentieth century. Early books described colonial educational systems. Later books in English compared different colonies' education systems. This topic was studied in detail by Cohen, who compared South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen said the large settler population in South West Africa made its educational system different. South West Africa was not as hot as other colonies. It had a moderate climate. The European population was large, with 15,000 whites living there in 1913. The next largest settler population was in East Africa, with 5,336 whites.

Popular music has many types. It is hard to count them all. Each type has many smaller types. One type is Heavy Metal. It started 40 years ago. It has many feelings, but mostly dark feelings. People made new types inside Heavy Metal. Today, it has many types and it is hard to know what Heavy Metal is. It comes from other music types. It is loud and has big drums. People in metal bands know how to play their instruments well. They use drugs to make their music. They like dark and wild things. Rock bands like the Beatles and the Rolling Stones changed music. Heavy Metal started from this change.

Henri Rousseau was a painter. He started painting his dreams. He dreamed of being famous. But he had a problem. He wanted to be unique. But he also wanted to be accepted by other artists. He painted a picture called The Dream. It shows a woman in a dream, like his own dreams. He started painting when he was older. He had no art school. He worked for France. He was happy to paint. He hoped people would like his art. But it was hard. Other artists were famous. He started to get famous when Matisse was famous too. He wanted to be like Matisse. But he also wanted to be different. He was like a simple man. He had simple dreams.

Many big thinkers have said that there is a close link between ethics and beauty. I think this is true. John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty -- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn many things through education or experience. But we often enjoy ethics and art without being taught about them in these ways. Ethics and art are ways to describe things, not to give rules. When we talk about art or morals, we can't completely explain why something is good or beautiful. People often say, "There's just something about it" when they talk about their favorite art or literature. This "something" is hard to explain. Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Ethics has this same mystery. Wittgenstein said, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This "something" is the most powerful part of art and morality. It connects ethics and aesthetics. Both are experienced, but can't be fully explained. This is why we feel them deeply. This is especially true for literature. McKean said, "Literature's moral quality sets it apart from other arts. Literature is important because of the values we find in it."

Germany is strong and united today. Its culture is special. It comes from different places. Germany is like this because it has many tribes and people. The name Germany comes from the Romans. They called the people Germans. The meaning is not sure. Some think it means a spear. Others think it means to shout. Before, the German tribes lived near the Romans. They traded and fought. They lived on the borders. They were not like the Romans. But they were close to the Roman Empire.

I saw the toilet. My mind was empty. I looked without feeling. I studied the picture, but did not think about it. Thoughts came and went quickly. I felt I was just seeing, not thinking.

I had tried to learn to draw. I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." This book taught me to see pictures in a simple way. It said to put a square frame around the picture to make it easy to understand.

The first time I tried this, I could not do it. The picture was too complicated. I was amazed. I thought about artists like Picasso and Monet. I thought about my drawing as my first story, "Work in Brown."

I tried to move the brown thing in the toilet. My hand moved. I was careful. But it was hard. The brown thing did not move. I decided to use the toilet paper to clean it.

I stood up. I held the mop. I thought about what I was doing. I dipped my hand into the toilet, like a mother putting a turkey into an oven. But this time, I succeeded. The brown thing moved. I cleaned the toilet.

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Several things make this happen. The teen brain is not ready for driving. They are also not experienced. This causes more accidents and other problems. Teens also have more accidents when they drive with friends. A study shows this.
California and other states have tried to make teens safer by limiting when they can drive and who can be in the car with them. But these rules are not enough. Teens are not ready to drive safely. A psychologist says 18 is too young to get a regular license. Teens want to take risks. It is better to wait until they are older to drive. If we do not change this, more teens will die in car accidents.
We can make a new law. Schools can teach driver's education. No one under 18 can drive. A permit can be issued before a full license. A certain number of practice hours can still be required. This will make teens safer. This law will help teens across the country.
This idea is not new.

I looked at old films in the Library of Congress. There were 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make illusions. I studied how they use different kinds of shots. Most trick films use a certain style. They stay in one place and show long shots or medium shots. The camera never moves. Actors often move side-to-side, but not towards or away from the camera.

Some films from the early 1900s break these rules. They use multiple shots. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors come in from the right and move back and forth. But the camera does not follow them.

Trick films often use long shots or medium shots. Close-up shots are never used. This is like the way plays and vaudeville shows are done. The audience sees the whole performance at once. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups do not happen.

Most early trick films have one shot for one concept. This makes the films short, usually about a minute. They are like vaudeville tricks. However, one shot can be made with many parts. Look at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). It seems like one shot, but it is made with many parts.

John Taylor from Caroline was a early supporter of Republican ideas. He worked mainly as a farmer, but his short time in politics made him known for his strong views on personal freedom and government. His love for farming shaped his beliefs about the government. He wanted to protect and encourage the best careers.

Taylor believed the United States could create an ideal system because there was no strong tradition to stop it. He thought everyone had natural rights, and these rights were connected. If one right was taken away, all rights lost value. He believed the government should not take these rights away.

Taylor wanted a government that understood human good and evil. He believed in a simple morality that protected property and helped farming. He thought a good government, even led by self-interested people, would be fair. But it must be careful to avoid adding bad rules.

Taylor wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He believed the federal government should have only the powers listed in the Constitution. He thought a strong federal government could be unfair. But he also thought literal interpretation could be bad if it ignored the writers' intentions. He saw the Declaration of Independence as the true document for the United States.

Looking at Figure 17, we saw a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was disappointing, and we don't know why it happened. Maybe winter and fewer people on campus explain some of it. December is also a busy month with schoolwork and holidays. People might not have time to fill out the log. March had more submissions after a special campaign, the Carpool Challenge Week. This helped, but we still had a problem with low participation during breaks. People like to drive their cars. To encourage other ways to commute, we offered prizes like gift cards. Maybe bigger prizes, like bikes or cars, could help. The project needed more engagement during breaks.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that follows an index, commodity, or group of assets. It trades like a stock and offers benefits like diversification, short selling, and buying on margin. ETFs usually have lower costs than mutual funds. However, you pay a commission when trading ETFs. Many types of ETFs are available. It's important to check if these benefits are real. We will examine ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings to see if owning one ETF is better than owning each stock separately.

We will only consider the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Below are these holdings and their percentages.

To see if the top 10 stocks represent the ETF well, we will calculate their Beta and return. The results are in the chart below.

The portfolio of the top 10 stocks has 6.11% higher return than the ETF, which is a 16% increase. The Beta is also 0.12 lower. So, the portfolio of the top 10 stocks seems better. However, we need to check if these portfolios are statistically different.

To check this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare it to the ETF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe's favorite poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule." Mabbott says this is from Virgil. Virgil used it for an island north of Britain, where Greeks thought the world ended. While Virgil used it, Poe might also have known it from a German author, Goethe.
This is important because it shows Poe's knowledge of Goethe's writing. Arndt says Poe's poem is similar to Goethe's. "The King of Thule" is a short poem in the second part of Faust. It is about a king who loses his wife and his will to live. This king is similar to the speaker in "Dream-Land."
Poe uses "Thule" twice in his writing. He uses "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and "Thule" in "Dream-Land." These poems can be read together. The speaker in "Dream-Land" describes Thule as dark and lonely, like the king in "The King of Thule." Poe might have known Goethe because he admired Tennyson, and Goethe's work was then being reproduced.

Under California law, could a customer injured by slipping on applesauce in a store be awarded punitive damages if the manager acted with malice?

No, a judge is not likely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim. To win, she must prove the manager acted with willful disregard for probable harm. She can show Martin knew of the danger because others had slipped before. He failed to clean the spill. His actions were bad, but reasonable.

On October 13, 2009, an employee told manager Paul Martin about an applesauce spill. Martin said he was eating and did not want to deal with it. A second employee also told him about the spill. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and got hurt. Before her accident, there were five slip-and-fall incidents in 2009.

California law lets a plaintiff get punitive damages if a defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." The manager’s conduct must be bad and willful. It is not enough if he just did not clean the spill. He must have known the danger and failed to avoid it.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We discussed if Islam is a hostile religion. This is still important today. After 9/11, media changed its view. In 2001, a Muslim president could not be elected. The Prophet Muhammad's story is interesting. His biography says he was humble and wise. But history says he was not. This is not fair to Jesus. The stories in the biography are not always true. They are told by people who heard from other people. This makes the stories seem less real. The biography tries to make Muhammad seem like a good man. But history says he was not. Muslims today might not know the real history of Muhammad.

Christianity changed after Jesus' life. It moved away from Jesus' teachings. Today, many people want to understand these teachings again. They want to know the facts of Jesus' ideas, not just what others added later. It will take time, but this will happen. Christians will return to Jesus' original beliefs. They will follow him directly. This will make the church strong again. It will be one religion with similar beliefs. History shows this kind of change before. It happened with the Roman Empire and African-American slavery. This change will happen in Christianity too. It will return to Jesus' original teachings. People will understand Jesus' words as they were meant: as metaphors, not as literal statements. This change will undo the diversity of beliefs. It will make Christianity more uniform. This is happening now. It will continue in the future.

I think The Jungle shows people are naturally selfish. They want to make their lives better, not help others. The book shows this in many ways. The big factory owners and managers only care about money. They do not care about animals or workers. The smoke from the factories hurts the environment. The owners do not care. They make their factories big and rich, even if it hurts people. They do not care about worker safety. They make people work long hours. If they need to, they fire workers without warning. There were no laws to protect workers. Managers and owners could do anything. Workers were treated like slaves. Some unions helped, but they made money from poor workers. Workers had no way to escape this system.

Some writers use tricks to make readers feel or think about important things. Scott Fitzgerald uses these tricks in his book The Great Gatsby. He often pairs words to make a special feeling. He also uses special meanings for symbols. Fitzgerald uses this trick with many colors. He builds meanings for colors like white/gray and red/pink. Then he uses these meanings to remind readers of feelings.

White/gray means like and important. Fitzgerald shows this in the start of the book. Daisy and Jordan often wear white. Many people at Gatsby's party wear white too. Fitzgerald also colors unimportant things white/gray. He says Nick is "white flannels" (41) at Gatsby's party, and the dog-seller is a "gray old man" (27).

Fitzgerald uses these meanings to show unimportant things. He does this with Daisy. After a long time, he says she is "dressed in white" (74). This makes her seem less important. He also uses gray haze of Daisy's fur collar (18) and her white dress (115) to show this.

San Diego County grows many crops. There is good weather there. People grow tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people buy organic food. There are long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Some farms give tours and have hiking areas. This helps people make money or learn about farming. Organic farming has more costs. It needs more work. It also has better plants and wildlife. The landowner might need help for organic farming.

The chosen land is near Potrero in San Diego County. It is 160 acres. It has chaparral, nonnative grass, and oak trees. It is near the Cleveland National Forest. Many plants and animals are there. Some are rare or might be rare soon. Some people lived there for many years. Cattle ranchers also lived there.

A person researched government programs to help with costs and help wildlife. They found an organic farm nearby. This is a model for what the landowner could do.

Culture is very important in any negotiation. Culture is what a group of people do and believe. It is not one single thing. It includes many different parts. It is not the same in every country or company. For example, some people think all Russians are stubborn. Some think all Japanese are helpful. These are broad generalizations.
A good negotiator needs to understand the culture of the other side. They must understand what the culture means and how it affects the negotiation. When someone meets a new culture, they compare it to their own culture.
To understand a culture, one might study its history or learn about its prejudices. One should accept the culture as it is, not try to change it. If you are the weaker side in a negotiation, respect the other culture.
Culture is not only about countries. Many companies have their own cultures. These can be different from family to family. Some companies are strict about work hours or how people talk. Some encourage helping others, others do not. Even in the same country, different companies can have different cultures.
Values are important. They explain why people do things. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not cause other people to feel embarrassed. If a culture values hard work, a negotiator will not give up quickly.
Before a negotiation, it is good to learn about the other side's culture and values. However, it is also good to know something about the other person personally.

St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas both believe in the existence of God. We will compare their arguments. It is hard to disprove God. They both think God exists. We will look at St. Anselm's argument. He says to look within yourself to find God. He says God is in our minds. He says we can understand God without outside proof. This is called faith. Thomas Aquinas says God can be proved with reason and evidence. He gives five arguments. He says God is needed for change, cause, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He says God is necessary for these things. Both have good points. Neither gives a complete reason for believing in God.

Many years ago, a man called Buddha was born. He became a teacher and started a religion. The main kind of this religion is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about 2,500 years old. It is different today than when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, a country where Theravada Buddhism is common, people do a water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is important for religion, even though Buddha did not teach about it. Theravada Buddhism has changed over time. This is because of many things, both good and bad, inside and outside the Buddhist community.

There are some important words used in this discussion. "Internal" means things inside the Buddhist community, like monks or laypeople. "External" means things outside the community. "Hostile" means things that hurt or try to hurt the Buddhist community. "Benign" means things that don't try to hurt the community, but might do so by mistake.

To understand Theravada Buddhism, we need to know its basic teachings. Buddhists believe in three things: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the teachings of Buddha. It is in three parts called the Tripitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has Buddha's words, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules for living, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about how things work. Important ideas in Buddhism include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (everything changes). Believing these things helps end the cycle of birth and death, and also helps end bad feelings like desire, hatred, and delusion. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life, like not killing, not lying, and not being drunk. The most important teaching in Buddhism is the four noble truths: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be ended, and there is a way to end it.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry. It lasted from 1836 to 1893. The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. The United States won and got new lands. Other fights happened, but they stopped before World War One.

Many nations have similar rivalries with their neighbors. They often fight about boundaries, religion, and culture. The United States and Mexico are not different. They had fights because of these issues.

Religious differences caused problems between the two nations. Americans did not like Catholicism and monarchy. This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. The rivalry ended when Mexico relied on the United States for help.

There were 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most were about who owned the land. Bandits and outlaws caused problems. The rivalry stopped when Mexico needed the United States for help and the United States stopped wanting more land.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly disabled by a sickness I did not know. I was a nurse at the time. I chose nursing because it seemed safe and secure. As a child, I did not have these things. I heard, "You will always find work. People will always need care." So, I chose nursing. I dreamed of being a scientist or journalist but chose nursing instead.

Now, I am 46 and disabled. I cannot work. I live on Social Security Disability. I have no money left. Every day is hard. Nothing is sure. Family and friends helped me. Without them, I could not have lived so long.

Life has emergencies, big and small. No one can overcome everything alone. We need to trust and help each other. We cannot rely only on big government. It is not strong. It is better to help each other and ask for help.

Conservatives talk about rugged individualism. But it was not this that helped our pioneers. It was compassion, respect, and sharing.

So, prepare for disasters. I have disaster kit, first aid, water purifying tablets, plastic for windows, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, canned goods. If you can farm, do it. But also, know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules or limits that influence how they change? D'Arcy Thompson in 1917 said: "Even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to describe organic forms in mathematical language." But today, math modeling helps understand mollusk shells. Our study uses math models and experiments to learn how mollusks change. We used X-ray images of Prunum shells to find numbers that help us create models. These models show possible shell shapes. We also study real and fake shells to understand big changes in this group. A shell is like a tube going around in space. Whorls are spirals around a center called the columella. The speed of these spirals can be different. The largest whorl is called the body whorl. The spire is the part without the last whorl. The animal exits the shell through the aperture. Shells can be seen from different sides. We count whorls by looking from the top and drawing a line. We can also draw the path of the aperture. This path can be shown with math. Once we have a math model, we can change numbers and see how the shell grows.

In Indonesia, neonatal and infant deaths have not improved much in ten years. While the country is doing well in some areas, like water and sanitation, it is not improving child and maternal health enough to meet goals by 2015. There are many reasons for this. We need to improve the whole health system, not just programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers now, but traditional workers like midwives cannot help with complicated pregnancies. This means many mothers die from bleeding. Also, fewer children under five are treated by health professionals for diarrhea. Postnatal care services are not available in many places.

Cesarian-section rates are low, 4%, and even lower in rural areas. This shows that healthcare is mainly available in cities. Also, richer people use more services than poorer people. The poor find it hard to get healthcare due to costs.

The next steps for improving care should involve fixing the lack of services. We should decide whether to improve specific programs or the whole health system. Program-specific approaches have clear goals and quick results. They also focus human resources and funding on one area. But they can hurt other areas and cause duplication and confusion.

Victorian novels are known for their focus on detail and attention to the rich life of the aristocracy. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, stand out. Both have mystery and unusual elements, which makes the characters strong and shows their inner thoughts. They often use these strange happenings in dreams or dreamlike states to reveal this.

In Oliver Twist, these events show Oliver's inner pain and fears. When he remembers being shot, he dreams of it. He is not in control and feels overwhelmed. He does not understand whose will caused his bad luck. He seems to accept his fate, which shows a sense of defeat. This happens because Fagin might be making him weak and unable to act.

In Wuthering Heights, these strange happenings also show the inner thoughts of the characters. They are often in love or anger, which shows their feelings. These events also show the power of nature and how it can change feelings and actions. The characters often change from good to bad and back again, which makes the story interesting.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program teaching elementary students. My best subjects were English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian, who was having trouble reading. He was in third or fourth grade and spoke perfect English. However, he had strange problems with reading. Some letters he pronounced perfectly, others he did not. He was of Latino descent. One day, his mother came. She spoke only Spanish. We communicated with my basic Spanish. Then I understood: Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well.

I tell this story to talk about language barriers in schools, especially in California. Many children speak English well, but have trouble reading. The solution for Adrian was simple: more English reading and alphabet tutoring. For children who barely speak English, the solution is harder. There is no one answer. We need different ways to help.

One good idea is the dual language system. It helps children whose first language is Spanish, and all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs do better academically." Many people think it is a waste of resources. However, if we use it more, all children will benefit. How can we do this? We do not need all teachers to be bilingual. We can have special bilingual aides or tutors.

From when we are young, many of us learn about something bigger than us. Some go to Sunday school, others to Temple or look inside themselves. Some accept their parents' beliefs, but others do not. We each find our own view of spirituality. We want light to guide us out of darkness.

"Cardinal," my father said when I asked. We sat, smoked, and listened to rain. He was thin, his hair less. He looked out, not at me. I felt alone, afraid. I hugged him, sat close. Rain fell.

My father died in December. I did not want to watch. I waited in bed for news. No one called.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is strange. Its name is "Old-New." It is both old and new. People have argued about it. Some say it is not deep. Others say it is terrible. It started with a story called "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. It used old and new things. It mixed old theater and new novels. This created the Gothic genre. It has old ideas from the Middle Ages. It also has new ideas.

One big idea in Gothic novels is Chivalry. Chivalry is the training of a knight. It is important because it was seen as a good ideal. In the novel "The Castle of Otranto," characters show this ideal. The main character, Frederic, is like a good knight. He is a prince. He suffers and is brave. The author, Walpole, may have felt this way because of his time. He was worried about the future. He thought the good in people was gone. His novel shows this idea.

Supply Chain Management is a process for moving goods from customer order to customer. This process includes raw materials, supply, production, and distribution. The term was created in 1982 by Keith Oliver. It covers planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to satisfy customers quickly and efficiently.

There are six key parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to serve customers well.

Production is the first step. It decides when, why, where, and how products are made. Managers use the market to understand customer demand. They then decide what and how many products to make. After that, they choose where to produce and which plant is best for volume and quality. Managers also focus on scheduling and equipment maintenance. Details are important in production.

Supply is the second key part. It involves making strategic decisions about facilities and outsourcing. A company may have many production divisions for one product. Managers choose the best fit for each division. They may also outsource work to create speed, quality, and flexibility while reducing costs.

Ellen Page holds sign in street. It says "Hitler alive in Burma."
Burma is country in Southeast Asia. It is ruled by group that came to power in 1962. They use military force.
In 2007, many people protest against this group. They are led by monks. The government does not allow protests. Many people are hurt or killed. Some are imprisoned.
This is not new. Many governments want to control their people. Some examples:
- Roman emperors said they were gods.
- Japanese emperors are said to be gods.
- U.S. president talks to Ted Haggard.
- June 4, 1989: People protest in China. Many are killed.
- 1990s: Tutsis killed in Rwanda.
- Hitler's Third Reich: Many Jews killed.

Duke Ellington's music is famous. He led his orchestra for a long time. He was a good composer. He wrote songs for each band member. He also brought the band's sound together. This made his music special. The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington used voice as a musical instrument. This is shown in Creole Love Call. In this song, the voice talks with other instruments. Ellington's voice sound changes. It starts smooth and ends rough. The song has six parts. In each part, voice and instruments talk. The music is complex and interesting. This is how Ellington used voice to add color to his music. In Hot and Bothered and It Don't Mean a Thing, Ellington uses this style too. He combines voice and instruments to make a new sound.

She always felt she needed something, but this desire was not fulfilled. It started when she was 14. It continued at 17. She wanted someone, not a thing. But no boy interested her. She wondered why. She lived life, questioning her desires. A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were calm. They argued only when she wanted independence. Today was not peaceful. She heard her mother scream. She ran to the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground. She asked, "Mom, what's wrong?" Her mother said, "I need help. Take me to the hospital." She carried her mother to the car and drove. The hospital was scary, but she was busy helping. Her mother fell from a stepping stool while trying to reach a vase.

This study showed that following the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a high alternate Mediterranean diet score, may reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The alternate Mediterranean diet is similar to the Mediterranean diet but has more plant foods, including nuts, whole grains, and legumes. It also has more monounsaturated fat and less saturated fat. A small amount of alcohol is allowed.

Earlier studies showed that the Mediterranean diet lowered the risk of death from heart disease and stroke. However, no studies focused on stroke. This study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, for 20 years. They filled out food frequency questionnaires six times. Many women stayed in the study for the full 20 years. The questionnaires were checked for accuracy.

The study found 2391 heart disease cases, 1763 stroke cases, and 1077 heart disease deaths. Women who ate the Mediterranean diet most closely were less likely to get heart disease or stroke. Women who ate the Mediterranean diet most closely had a 29% lower risk of heart disease and a 24% lower risk of stroke.

In 2007, the United States had a big money problem. People lost jobs, homes, and companies went broke. Many big banks were also in trouble. We need to know how this happened and how to fix it. The problem started with poor decisions by politicians. They made banks give loans to people who could not pay back. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac helped with these loans. When people did not pay, banks had problems. The economy was hurt. In 1999, President Clinton made it easier for people to get loans. This led to the crisis. Many people and companies were hurt. The housing market was a mess. Banks gave loans to people who could not pay. This made the economy very weak. When the housing market stopped giving, banks had big problems. Many banks were sold or closed. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in bad loans and were taken over by the government.

Exposition in story can be good or bad. If it is good, it helps us understand what happened. If it is bad, it can be boring or too much information. Dr. Merlin knows this, but sometimes she makes mistakes.

Some writers know the tip "Show, don't tell." This means to show things in the story, not just tell us about them. But even with this tip, writers can make mistakes. They can tell too much or not enough.

Exposition means telling us what happened, often in simple words. It can happen when one character tells another about something, like in a play. In books, the writer does the telling.

An example: Suppose a story says a man and woman met, got married, and then the man died. We don't want to read pages about this if nothing happens. We want to see the man and woman interact, feel their love. We want to see his character through his words and actions. Then, when he dies, we will feel sad for the woman and understand her more.

As a writer, you should give us this detail. Sometimes we rush to tell about new characters. We might say they were in the Air Force, now work at a gas station, have no kids, like fishing, and dream of owning the gas station. But we don't show their personality, their feelings. We should show these things.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first was "live" on NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture and said he was arrested. They talked about this for two minutes. I think this was enough time.

The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. A man named Travis Buyers, 18, was shot and hurt badly. No one was arrested yet. The SWAT team was looking for the shooter. This story was short, and I think it was because the victim was black. I have noticed this before—the media often does not cover crimes against minorities well.

The next story was about a gunshot hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was from a rifle and offered a $5,000 reward for information.

Another story was about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. They talked a lot about his skin color and how tall he was. This seemed unusual.

The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin. He was sentenced to "300" months in prison for selling marijuana from Texas to Ohio. They also said he was Hispanic, but I don't think this was important to the story.

There is a strong bond between brothers. This bond is like a rope that cannot be broken. Inside this bond are many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers know each other very well. They can see themselves in their brother. When things are bad, the true nature of this bond appears. Sometimes, this bond brings good feelings. Sometimes, it brings bad feelings. Brothers must deal with these feelings. When one brother looks at another, they see their own face. They see themselves as others do, not as they are. Their actions and the results show their true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme. They go on a journey in a beautiful, green land. They feel many strong feelings. In the end, only one brother lives. The main character, Doodle, shows this theme. His feelings and actions show the theme. The place where he lives, the way he sees the world, and his feelings about his brother influence him. The main character has one big feeling: pride. He wants his brother to be like him. He wants to teach his brother skills like holding breath, running, jumping, and climbing trees. He wants to race to Horsehead Landing and perch in a tree. But his brother, Doodle, is not strong. He has a weak heart. He cannot do these things. The main character feels sad and angry. He thinks about killing Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him. This smile makes the main character feel better. It shows that the main character loves his brother.

The human brain is a complicated system that processes information. As technology changed from simple to modern, the ways we describe the brain also changed. Early, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer. Remember, these comparisons are limited and can be wrong.
Information starts with signals from our senses. These signals turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, and light into electrical signals. The brain turns these signals into information. It does this in two ways, bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up processing looks at simple things, like color and shape, to decide what we are seeing. Top-down processing uses the brain's past decisions to help us recognize things faster. For example, when we see a black box, top-down processing might make us think it is a real box, not just a hole.
The brain decides which information is important. This is called attention. For example, we don't notice every blade of grass when looking at our shoes, but we hear our name in a noisy room. There are many steps in processing information, and attention helps decide what we focus on.
Information must be stored for the brain to process it. There are many types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. Information is encoded, or turned into something the brain can understand. It is then stored. Some studies say working memory, which stores information for 20 seconds, uses an electrical signal looping through neurons. Long-term memory is thought to be stored in protein structures.
There are many ways to describe how the brain organizes knowledge. Some are based on how people remember things, others on computer science, and others on biology. The semantic network model says there are nodes for concepts, and these nodes are linked based on how related they are. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” and “wooden.”

Aldous Huxley criticizes the future danger of technology and capitalism in his novel Brave New World. The people in this world value the group more than the individual. They are trained to seek happiness and not think about different ideas. The people are like pieces in a big game, following the rules set by the World Controller. By looking at the novel using Marxist ideas, one sees the author's worry about these systems.

Capitalism is shown as a trick. People do not know the real truth about money and classes. They only think about their own gain. This is because the ruling class controls their thoughts. The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, want to buy and enjoy things more than anything else. This is because the World Controller makes them want it. The rich people know this, but they do not do anything. Most people in the novel do not think about their place in society. They only think about what they want.

People in Brave New World do not have deep relationships. They only talk about their work and bodies. They do not feel love or strong emotions. This shows that technology and capitalism might take away people's free will and feelings. The novel's characters do not think about their place in society. They just follow the rules.

I have been a student at University Park for two years and four semesters. Getting around campus is difficult. My first year, I lived in East Halls. It was far from classes. Traveling took 25 minutes by foot. Conditions were bad, but now the area has changed. It's full of sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. This makes travel more difficult. Bicycles are the best solution. But they need to be used. The campus must be built for bicyclists. I live off campus now. It's far from the center. Buying a bike was the best decision. It saves time. I have class in Thomas building. On foot, it takes 25 minutes. On a bike, it's 5 minutes. Pollock Road is a direct route, but it's not easy. Walking is possible, but I don't have time. Without a bike, walking would be my only option. It would take 30-40 minutes. That's 2.5 hours a week. That's too much time.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.  Though these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good exercise for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether stated benefits, like diversification, do indeed exist, and the extent to which they exist.  For the purposes of this effort, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it against the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of a owning a single ETF come close to the benefits of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also whether or not there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal sharp ratio or return.
	In order to evaluate the ETF, it would become rather unwieldy to include every holding, therefore we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF.  Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

	In order to gain an estimation of how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to  calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolioâ€™s Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings.  The calculations of Beta and return are included in the below chart.

From the above chart it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is .12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta.  However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.
	In order to evaluate whether or not these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a precipitous drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. That was a bit disheartening, and it is hard to say why that might have happened. With the onset of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting either by bicycle or by foot, which may account for some portion of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is very busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so forth. Filling out the commuter log might just have slipped off the radar screen for many folks. In addition, December brings the onset of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which time many do not even need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume for the spring semester in late January, perhaps also a clue to the low number of logs for that month. But none of that really explains the low number of submissions for February. One might also conjecture that any project of this type is going to have an initial burst of energy and excitement at the outset, which might then naturally decline. In an effort to combat this trend, we created the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to try and reinvigorate the initiative, which did result in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we experienced was how to maintain project momentum in the face of both a natural decrease in engagement, but also specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education. 
Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative modes of commuting. We gave out a lot prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see, however, how some even larger prizes might have affected participation – such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped to combat that dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change during the course of the project. If the prizes, however, were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed to be more than adequate at the outset of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participating and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films.
